                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d94">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 893.00/2424</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Minister <persName type="from">Reinsch</persName> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegrams]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Peking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-06-06T22:00:00+08:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">June 6, 10 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Having been assured of support of Tuan and the Cabinet, General Li intends to
                    take oath of office tomorrow morning as President.<note n="5" xml:id="d94fn5">
                        <hi rend="italic">See</hi> Death of President Yuan Shih-kai and succession
                        of President Li Yuan-hung, post, <ref target="#pg_98">p. 98</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>The British and Allied Ministers have meanwhile jointly approached the Foreign
                    Office and Tuan as Premier with an intimation of their hope that the presidency
                    would be allowed to devolve constitutionally upon Li and that the Government
                    would be able to accomplish the transfer of authority without disorder. The
                    British and Belgian Ministers have informed the Legation that Tuan gave
                    satisfactory assurances on these points and furthermore expressed his hope that
                    the new situation would make possible reconciliation of the seceding
                    provinces.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Reinsch</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
